<section class="article">
  <div class="article-grid">
    <aside class="article-sidebar">
      <div class="article-sidebar-title">On this page</div>
      <ul>
        <li><a href="#warrants">Two kinds of warrants</a></li>
        <li><a href="#what-to-do">What you can do</a></li>
        <li><a href="#what-to-provide">What you must provide</a></li>
        <li><a href="#categories">Stopped vs. detained vs. arrested</a></li>
        <li><a href="#searches">Your rights during searches</a></li>
        <li><a href="#ice-detention">In ICE detention</a></li>
        <li><a href="#phrases">Key phrases</a></li>
        <li><a href="#citations">Sources</a></li>
      </ul>
    </aside>

    <article class="prose">
      <p>Choosing to stay silent or to refuse a search cannot be used against you in court as evidence that you are guilty of something. The Constitution protects you from this. The Fourth Amendment protects you from unreasonable searches and seizures, and the Fifth Amendment protects you from being forced to say things that could be used to incriminate yourself.<sup>1</sup></p>

      <h2 id="warrants">Two kinds of warrants</h2>
      <p>There is an important distinction between the types of warrants officers may present. A <strong>judicial warrant</strong> is signed by a judge and carries the full authority of the court. An <strong>administrative warrant</strong> — such as Form I-200, which is issued and signed by an ICE supervisor — does not carry the same legal weight. You are not legally required to open your door for an administrative warrant.<sup>2</sup></p>

      <h2 id="what-to-do">What you can do</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Remain calm and do not physically resist, even if you believe the stop is unlawful. Resisting can escalate the situation and may result in additional charges.</li>
        <li>If an officer asks to search you or your belongings, you may say clearly: <em>“I do not consent to a search.”</em> Even if officers proceed with the search, your verbal objection preserves your legal rights and may be important in court later.<sup>3</sup></li>
        <li>Ask: <em>“Am I free to go?”</em> If the officer says yes, walk away calmly. If the answer is no, you are being detained, and you should ask for an attorney.</li>
        <li>If you are not free to go, say: <em>“I want to speak to a lawyer.”</em> Say this clearly and, if necessary, repeat it. Once you have requested a lawyer, you are not required to answer further questions.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="what-to-provide">What you are required to provide — and to whom</h2>
      <p>If you are stopped by a <strong>local police officer</strong>, you are generally required to provide your name and, in some states, to show a state-issued ID if you have one. You are not required to answer questions about your immigration status, country of birth, or how you entered the United States. Local police in most jurisdictions do not have immigration enforcement authority.<sup>4</sup></p>
      <p>If you are stopped by an <strong>ICE or CBP agent</strong>, you must provide your name and show immigration documents if you have them (such as a green card, visa, or EAD). However, you may refuse to answer substantive questions — such as where you were born, how you entered the country, or your immigration history — by invoking your right to remain silent.<sup>5</sup></p>
      <p>In either situation, <strong>do not lie or present false documents.</strong> Making false statements to a federal agent is a federal crime, punishable by up to five years in prison.<sup>6</sup></p>
      <p>If you are arrested, officers must inform you of your <em>Miranda</em> rights before conducting a custodial interrogation: that you have the right to remain silent, that anything you say can be used against you in court, that you have the right to a lawyer, and that if you cannot afford a lawyer one will be provided in a criminal case. Statements made before these warnings are given may be inadmissible in court, though limited exceptions exist.<sup>7</sup></p>

      <h2 id="categories">Stopped, questioned, detained, arrested</h2>
      <p>These terms have specific legal meanings, and the rights you have depend on which situation you are in.</p>

      <div class="table-wrap">
        <table class="kyr">
          <thead>
            <tr><th>Situation</th><th>Your rights</th></tr>
          </thead>
          <tbody>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Briefly stopped for questioning</strong><br /><span class="muted">An officer approaches you and asks questions in a brief encounter — often on the street, in a car, or at your workplace.</span></td>
              <td>You must provide your name if asked. You may ask <em>“Am I free to go?”</em> If yes, leave calmly. You do not have to answer questions about your immigration status (unless the officer is ICE or CBP — see above).</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Stopped &amp; questioned by ICE or CBP</strong><br /><span class="muted">An ICE or CBP agent approaches you, often at a checkpoint, workplace raid, or your home, and identifies themselves as immigration officers.</span></td>
              <td>You must provide your name and immigration documents if you have them. You may decline to answer substantive questions about your immigration history. Say: <em>“I am exercising my right to remain silent. I would like to speak to a lawyer.”</em></td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Detained</strong> (not free to leave, but not formally arrested)<br /><span class="muted">If you ask “Am I being detained?” and the officer says yes — or tells you that you are not free to leave — you are detained. Detention is temporary and investigative.</span></td>
              <td>You have the right to remain silent. You may ask: <em>“Why am I being detained?”</em> You do not have a right to a government-appointed attorney during a brief investigative detention, but you may request to contact one. Do not sign anything without legal advice.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
              <td><strong>Arrested</strong> (formally placed in custody)<br /><span class="muted">An officer tells you that you are under arrest, places you in handcuffs, or reads you your rights. You are taken into custody.</span></td>
              <td>You have the right to remain silent. You have the right to know the charges against you. You have the right to an attorney — in criminal proceedings, one will be appointed if you cannot afford one. <strong>In immigration proceedings, you must obtain your own attorney.</strong> Say: <em>“I want to speak to a lawyer”</em> and remain silent.</td>
            </tr>
          </tbody>
        </table>
      </div>

      <div class="callout callout-info">
        <div class="callout-title">Detention vs. arrest, in one paragraph</div>
        <p>Detention is temporary — officers hold you briefly while they investigate. During a brief investigative detention, you do not have the right to a government-appointed attorney, though you may request to contact one. Arrest means you are formally in custody and will be processed through the criminal or immigration system. In criminal cases, you have the right to a court-appointed attorney if you cannot afford one. In immigration cases, you have the right to an attorney, but the government will not appoint one for you — you must find and pay for your own, or seek free legal aid.<sup>8</sup></p>
      </div>

      <p>If you are placed in immigration proceedings, you can ask the immigration judge or the officer holding you for a <strong>List of Pro Bono Legal Service Providers</strong>. The Department of Justice maintains this list of free or low-cost organizations that may be able to represent you, and you have the right to receive a copy.</p>

      <h2 id="searches">Your rights regarding searches</h2>
      <p>During a routine stop, an officer may conduct a limited pat-down of your outer clothing if the officer has reasonable suspicion that you may be armed. This does not require your consent. However, a more thorough search of your person — such as going through your pockets — generally requires either your consent, a warrant, or a lawful arrest.<sup>9</sup></p>
      <p>Your belongings (bags, backpack, vehicle) may be searched if you give consent, if officers have a warrant, or in certain circumstances such as a search incident to arrest. If you do not consent, say clearly: <em>“I do not consent to a search of my belongings.”</em> Even if officers proceed, your objection is legally preserved.</p>
      <p>Searches at the border are different. At airports, ports of entry, and other border locations, Customs and Border Protection officers may search your belongings, including phones and laptops, with broader authority than police elsewhere. Your verbal objection is still recorded for legal purposes, and CBP cannot deny a U.S. citizen entry into the country, but they may delay you while they conduct a search. See <a href="airports-borders.html">Airports &amp; Borders</a> for more.</p>

      <h2 id="ice-detention">What you should know about ICE detention</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>You have the right to remain silent</strong> — use it. Anything you say can and will be used against you.</li>
        <li><strong>You have the right to be represented by an attorney.</strong> However, in immigration proceedings, the government will not appoint one for you. You must hire your own attorney or seek assistance from a nonprofit legal aid organization. IALDF maintains a list of resources that may help.<sup>10</sup></li>
        <li><strong>You have the right to know why you are being held.</strong> The officers must inform you of the basis for your detention.</li>
        <li><strong>You have the right to a phone call.</strong> Ask: <em>“May I make a phone call?”</em> Use it to contact a lawyer, family member, or trusted friend.</li>
        <li>If you are arrested on criminal charges, you have the right to a <strong>probable-cause determination hearing within 72 hours</strong> of your arrest.<sup>11</sup></li>
      </ul>

      <h2 id="phrases">Key phrases you can use</h2>
      <ul class="phrase-list">
        <li>
          <div class="situation">If you are stopped by police or ICE</div>
          <div class="what">“I do not consent to a search.” If arrested: “I want to speak to a lawyer.” Then remain silent.</div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div class="situation">If you are asked for documents — by police</div>
          <div class="what">Provide your name and state ID. You do not have to answer immigration questions.</div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div class="situation">If you are asked for documents — by ICE or CBP</div>
          <div class="what">Provide your name and immigration documents if you have them. Then: “I am exercising my right to remain silent.”</div>
        </li>
        <li>
          <div class="situation">If you are asked questions about your immigration history</div>
          <div class="what">“I am exercising my right to remain silent. I would like to speak to a lawyer.”</div>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div class="callout callout-warn">
        <div class="callout-title">Carry the wallet card</div>
        <p>A ready-made rights card with these phrases in English and Farsi is available as a separate downloadable document. Print it, laminate if possible, and keep it near your front door or in your wallet. <a href="../templates.html">Get the card →</a></p>
      </div>

      <details class="citations" id="citations">
        <summary>Sources — Police & ICE encounters</summary>
        <ol>
          <li>U.S. Constitution, Fourth and Fifth Amendments (protection against unreasonable searches and seizures; right against self-incrimination).</li>
          <li>8 U.S.C. § 1226(a); 8 C.F.R. § 287.3 (ICE administrative warrants — Form I-200 authority, distinguished from judicial warrants).</li>
          <li><em>Schneckloth v. Bustamonte</em>, 412 U.S. 224 (1974) (verbal objection to search preserves legal rights).</li>
          <li><em>United States v. Brignoni-Ponce</em>, 422 U.S. 873 (1975); state “stop and identify” statutes vary — local police generally cannot demand immigration documents.</li>
          <li>8 U.S.C. § 1357(a)(2) (ICE/CBP authority to interrogate and require immigration documents).</li>
          <li>18 U.S.C. § 1001 (false statements to federal agents — up to 5 years imprisonment).</li>
          <li><em>Miranda v. Arizona</em>, 384 U.S. 436 (1966).</li>
          <li>8 U.S.C. § 1362 (right to counsel in immigration proceedings — at no expense to the government); <em>Padilla v. Kentucky</em>, 559 U.S. 356 (2010).</li>
          <li><em>Terry v. Ohio</em>, 392 U.S. 1 (1968) (limited pat-down with reasonable suspicion).</li>
          <li>8 U.S.C. § 1362 (right to counsel at own expense in immigration proceedings — no right to government-appointed attorney).</li>
          <li><em>County of Riverside v. McLaughlin</em>, 500 U.S. 44 (1991) (72-hour probable-cause hearing for criminal arrests).</li>
        </ol>
      </details>

